.net/~neoleo/color.gif class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/ueljefemariaci.showPublicProfile?language=EN>El Jefe Mariaci</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>poon</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/19/01 2:58:53 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Bwazoooooo!</span><hr size=1>        <br>
      The one thing that I learned from Speech before I dropped the class was that to disregard what a speaker has to say for any reason other than the content itself is fallacy.<br>
<br>
      Jo has a lot of emotion behind his argument, but that is not to say he doesn't make several valid points. As I am 19 now, I am forced to look at the consequences of my actions, in this life any number of possibilities can hit me, and can alter my life permanently. Like last night.. I could have driven home drunk and killed some one but instead I crashed at my friends house. Should I have killed some one, there would be no second chances.<br>
<br>
     Its kind of the same with having unprotected sex. You know you have a good chance by having sex that the sperm will fertilize the egg and you will have life. Now the reason abortion exists is because sex is something that is esteemed so highly as a past time that people refuse to accept the fact that there can be serious consequences for their &quot;good time.&quot; But isn't that life? We are not here to be tools of a self-serving consumer culture, I believe we need to aspire to greater goals; and abortion is wrong.<br>
<br>
     Why does the life of the fetus matter? Because if the woman continues to live that fetus will grow into a human, just like if an infant continues to survive it will grow into an adult. The level of maturity of a person is not dependent on it being considered a person. It will grow if the mother continues to survive, making it a human. The reason there is debate over whether it is considered a human or not is all in justification.<br>
<br>
We can always justify anything we feel.<br>
<br>
    What about the life of the child when it is born? That is not for you, the doctor, or even the parents to decide. Happiness isn't dependent on money. If the child is brought up in a foster home would it rather be dead? Thats not for any one person to predict or decide. What you have with the argument that the kid would be better off dead is simply another justification for implementing abortion, people are so emotionally involved in the issue that they seek to defend their position using any means.<br>
<br>
     Here is the bottom line. Man suffers. We all have. To any degree, I am a child of divorce and I suffer just as much as those whose parents are together. Its all in perception. Planned children may be more miserable that the non planned, no one can tell. Its not for you to decide whether or not a person will have a happy life.<br>
<br>
     Now, Cyp, I heard you say &quot;If the child is going to be raised off tv and ritz crackers, the parents should just abort.&quot; <br>
<br>
     I was raised off tv and ritz crackers.<br>
<br>
     My parents took little interest in my affairs. Does it make me any less content in life? No. If anything I think that makes me more emotionally strong than others. I learned to develop my philosophies and opinions on my own, and I like who I am in the end result, and I like that I am still learning in life, becoming a better person each day (some days are worse than others) but I would definately opt to be alive over dead and I believe that most kids that &quot;are going through hell&quot; would agree with me. If you don't believe it, go to the foster homes and tell the kids they are being put to sleep and see if they rejoice. <br>
<br>
     If I have said it a million times in this post, I will say it again. No one has the right to determine whether or not a human will be &quot;better off dead&quot;<br>
<br>
- El Jefe -<br>
<br>
